 How Stencil Actually Works — The Full Mental Model

  1. The Big Picture: What Stencil IS

  Stencil is not a framework. It is a compiler.

  You write components in TypeScript + JSX. Stencil compiles them into native Web Components — a browser standard. That output has zero dependency on
  Stencil at runtime.

  Your Code (TypeScript + JSX)
          ↓
     Stencil Compiler
          ↓
  Native Web Components (plain JS, works everywhere)

  This is why companies like Ionic, Adobe (Spectrum), and Microsoft (FAST) use it for design systems — you build once, ship to React, Angular, Vue, or plain
   HTML. No framework lock-in.

  ---
  2. Web Components — The Browser Standard Stencil Compiles To

  The browser natively supports 3 technologies that make Web Components possible:

  ┌─────────────────┬───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │   Technology    │                             What it does                              │
  ├─────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Custom Elements │ Lets you define <my-button> as a real HTML tag                        │
  ├─────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Shadow DOM      │ Encapsulates styles — your CSS can't leak out, page CSS can't leak in │
  ├─────────────────┼───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ HTML Templates  │ Efficient DOM stamping                                                │
  └─────────────────┴───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Stencil writes all that boilerplate for you. You just write the logic.

  ---
  3. The Anatomy of a Stencil Component

  Every component is a TypeScript class decorated with decorators that tell the compiler what to do.

  import { Component, Prop, State, Event, EventEmitter, Listen, h } from '@stencil/core';

  @Component({
    tag: 'my-button',        // → the HTML tag name (must have a dash)
    styleUrl: 'my-button.css', // → scoped CSS file
    shadow: true,            // → enables Shadow DOM isolation
  })
  export class MyButton {

    // ─── INPUTS FROM OUTSIDE ────────────────────────────────
    @Prop() label: string;        // <my-button label="Click me">
    @Prop() disabled: boolean = false;

    // ─── INTERNAL STATE (triggers re-render when changed) ───
    @State() clickCount: number = 0;

    // ─── OUTPUTS (events this component fires) ───────────────
    @Event() buttonClicked: EventEmitter<number>;

    // ─── LIFECYCLE HOOKS ─────────────────────────────────────
    componentDidLoad() {
      // runs once after first render — like useEffect(fn, [])
    }

    // ─── METHODS ─────────────────────────────────────────────
    handleClick() {
      this.clickCount++;                        // @State change → auto re-render
      this.buttonClicked.emit(this.clickCount); // fire event up to parent
    }

    // ─── TEMPLATE (what gets rendered as HTML) ────────────────
    render() {
      return (
        <button disabled={this.disabled} onClick={() => this.handleClick()}>
          {this.label} — clicked {this.clickCount} times
        </button>
      );
    }
  }

  The 5 Core Decorators You Must Master

  @Component  → class-level config (tag, styles, shadow)
  @Prop       → INPUT  — data flows IN  (parent → component)
  @State      → INTERNAL — reactive data, triggers re-render
  @Event      → OUTPUT — data flows OUT (component → parent)
  @Listen     → LISTENER — reacts to events from children

  ---
  4. How the Render Cycle Works

  This is the heart of Stencil. Understanding this = understanding reactivity.

  Initial load
      │
      ▼
  componentWillLoad()   ← async allowed, delays first render
      │
      ▼
  render()              ← returns JSX → becomes real DOM
      │
      ▼
  componentDidLoad()    ← DOM is ready, refs available
      │
      ▼
      ┌─────────────────────────────────┐
      │  @Prop or @State changes        │
      │         │                       │
      │         ▼                       │
      │  componentShouldUpdate()        │ ← can block re-render
      │         │                       │
      │         ▼                       │
      │  componentWillUpdate()          │
      │         │                       │
      │         ▼                       │
      │      render()                   │ ← virtual DOM diff
      │         │                       │
      │         ▼                       │
      │  componentDidUpdate()           │
      └─────────────────────────────────┘

  Key rule: Only @Prop and @State changes trigger re-renders. A plain this.myVar = x does nothing. You must use @State for reactive data.

