  6. How a Design System is Structured with Stencil

  A design system is just a published npm package of components. Here's the architecture:

  my-design-system/
  ├── src/
  │   ├── components/
  │   │   ├── button/          ← ds-button
  │   │   ├── input/           ← ds-input
  │   │   ├── card/            ← ds-card
  │   │   └── modal/           ← ds-modal
  │   └── global/
  │       └── tokens.css       ← design tokens (colors, spacing, typography)
  ├── stencil.config.ts        ← outputs: dist + custom-elements
  └── package.json             ← published to npm

  Design tokens are the foundation — CSS custom properties that all components reference:

  /* tokens.css */
  :root {
    --color-primary: #0070f3;
    --color-danger:  #e00;
    --spacing-sm:    8px;
    --spacing-md:    16px;
    --radius-md:     8px;
    --font-body:     'Inter', sans-serif;
  }

  Every component uses tokens instead of hardcoded values. Change a token → every component updates. That's the power.

  ---
  7. The Build Output — What Gets Distributed

  Your stencil.config.ts produces two outputs:

  dist/                    ← full package (lazy-loading, works in any app)
    └── my-stencil-learn.esm.js  ← loads only components used on the page

  dist/components/         ← individual components (tree-shakeable)
    └── my-button.js       ← import just this one component

  A React app can use your design system like:
  import { MyButton } from 'my-design-system/my-button';

  An Angular app, Vue app, or plain HTML page can all use the exact same built output.

  ---
  8. The God-Level Roadmap

  Here's what mastery looks like, in order:

  Level 1 — Components
    @Component, @Prop, render(), CSS scoping

  Level 2 — Reactivity
    @State, lifecycle hooks, conditional rendering, lists

  Level 3 — Communication
    @Event, @EventEmitter, @Listen, @Method (expose public API)

  Level 4 — Design Tokens
    CSS custom properties, global styles, theming

  Level 5 — Component Composition
    slots (<slot>), named slots, slot fallbacks

  Level 6 — Advanced Patterns
    @Element (ref to host), @Watch (react to Prop changes),
    Stencil stores (cross-component state), portals

  Level 7 — Distribution
    npm publish, React/Angular/Vue wrappers, Storybook integration